{"id":"d=origam-topic-4384//p=eb2987cda98e422a93eda082f92a094c","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4384"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["d5eefcec39c64b79bdb219e171efa661"],"__file_part":["debf939dc54a490db01535441eb3bd9e"],"__part_n":["0"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["4384"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-create-split-screens-with-tabs/4384"],"title":["How to create Split Screens with Tabs"],"imagesFound":["11"],"imagesDescribed":["11"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/bdc342a15830fe93cae1efc7a721e8ab5c24eb26.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a7497b3947c259965b473bc301b6a1c13ed40624.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6c5c415561b9a1dc2673fa8727a35775c4025776.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/cec5c6a6b32c3007b068f0e7d124ad7452421d8e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f4f83676a7411429092ef4414647a234e8d3780c.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/cff6ac31a6ba1cd56a62ef36afe4d466030e8c83.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/9/990aa0a613ad11fa9ebf1973c6e4254c928f5d16.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/415b4e2ea8164916275e29bf4e2f7888ea304dc0.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/24ed9c427ff575e546b5a5a77eeae579b6a5b5dc.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/2323b999560b2ca3948a9437495124dcd4efc5cb.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/42a3c64dc423ac692a1a0d703feb485951da34cd.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# How to create Split Screens with Tabs\n\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-create-split-screens-with-tabs/4384\n\n@vikter (2026-03-07 16:58:52Z):\n   \n This guide shows how to create  split screens  \u2014 screens divided into two separate parts that can be linked together. Sometimes this type of display is also referred to as a  master-detail screen . In addition to that it shows as well how  tabs  can be used in screen sections. It is a continuation of the first part named  How to create Screens . \n As an example, we will use the  Task Manager app . \n   Introduction \n To better understand what we are about to demonstrate, have a look at this split screen: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/bdc342a15830fe93cae1efc7a721e8ab5c24eb26.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a \u0022Task overview\u0022 section, featuring a list of tasks assigned to different users. It includes a dropdown list for users with three entries: Viktor Ter, Mark Pistorius, and John Doe. Below this, a table presents tasks with the following columns: Name, Description, Priority, Due date, and Status. The tasks listed are \u0022Add new users,\u0022 \u0022Insert all team tasks,\u0022 \u0022Prepare project kick-off,\u0022 and \u0022Finalize the analysis,\u0022 each with corresponding descriptions, priority levels (Mid or High), due dates (ranging from 02/28/2026 to 03/31/2026), and statuses (New or In Progress). The interface indicates pagination with controls at the bottom, allowing navigation through multiple pages of tasks.\n\n\n  \n In the upper part of the screen there is a list of existing users. When you click on any of them, you can see the tasks assigned to the selected user in the bottom part of the screen. In addition, you can switch tabs and view different items related to the selected user \u2014 open or completed tasks in this example. \n To create such a screen you need to link the entities in both parts of the split screen, as well as create screen sections used in both parts and all the tabs. This tutorial will show you how to do that. \n   Preparations \n Before we start creating the split screen itself, we need to prepare some model structures for it. \n   Entity relationship \u0026 key \n To link the entities in the split screen \u2014 users and their tasks in this example \u2014 you need to create a relationship between them and also a key that relates particular fields from both entities. \n The relationship should be created on the parent entity, which in this example is the system entity  BusinessPartner  that represents the user in ORIGAM: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a7497b3947c259965b473bc301b6a1c13ed40624.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a user interface for a software application related to Partner Management. The visible navigation tree includes categories such as \u0022BusinessPartner,\u0022 displaying sub-items like \u0022_Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Fields,\u0022 \u0022Filters,\u0022 \u0022Indexes,\u0022 and \u0022Parameters.\u0022 Under the \u0022Relationships\u0022 section, there is a highlighted option labeled \u0022Relationship,\u0022 with a dropdown menu featuring options like \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 \u0022Repeat New (F12),\u0022 \u0022Actions,\u0022 and \u0022Convert To.\u0022 The apparent purpose of this interface is to manage and configure business partner relationships within the application.\n\n\n  \n This relationship is of type \u201Cparent-child\u201D ( IsParentChild = True ), where the user ( BusinessPartner ) is the parent and the task is its child. Therefore the  Task  entity is specified as the  RelatedEntity : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6c5c415561b9a1dc2673fa8727a35775c4025776.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a relationship editor, labeled \u0022Relationship: Task.\u0022 In the \u0022Info\u0022 section under \u0022(Schema Item),\u0022 there are fields with the following visible text: \u0022Ancestors,\u0022 marked as True; \u0022Inheritable,\u0022 also marked as True; and \u0022Name,\u0022 which is set to \u0022Task.\u0022 In the \u0022Misc\u0022 section, the fields include \u0022IsOR\u0022 (False), \u0022IsParentChild\u0022 (True), \u0022IsSelfJoin\u0022 (False), and \u0022RelatedEntity\u0022 (noted as \u0022Task\u0022 with an associated icon). The apparent purpose of this interface is to manage and configure properties related to a data relationship in a schema.\n\n\n  \n Once the relationship is created, you can add a key to it. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:59:35"},"vector":[-0.0065986402,-0.010814012,-0.055824265,0.0323668,-0.018719066,0.024447052,0.027889917,-0.007415759,-0.001779902,0.018784437,0.018432764,0.00074003875,-0.008177341,0.02704885,0.0062791044,-0.03375268,-0.00031824547,-0.0033501966,0.026015064,0.012116408,0.0040231626,-0.013898026,0.014068684,0.017950108,0.02150583,0.04560918,-0.014315709,-0.019914942,0.031833496,-0.022003848,0.038862485,-0.069649175,0.0061277742,-0.04162293,-0.008058528,-0.036621016,-0.030550934,0.0023241409,-0.03038734,0.001541025,-0.037684966,-0.0007505662,0.0077672387,-0.025524547,-0.025573242,-0.011451327,-0.024381917,-0.0079809325,-0.008310275,-0.025779285,-0.06521473,0.005797867,0.03499452,-0.008050088,0.041647244,0.06505529,-0.072953224,-0.009060493,-0.058516596,0.015392376,-0.013616996,0.0076527055,0.0134108765,-0.010681828,0.010643579,0.04434448,0.0043716105,0.025010662,-0.006702644,-0.02327759,-0.024219388,0.05086955,-0.0036487621,-0.042855855,-0.051785238,0.00787185,0.004135755,0.016811578,-0.01384445,0.008492161,-0.033114597,0.0026559406,0.02526221,-0.008245272,-0.0112487385,0.008577837,-0.052030258,0.08766431,0.028697774,0.0018409651,-0.039390616,-0.015337542,0.05616065,-0.04763273,0.020331569,-0.0011948294,-0.0068373797,0.007461798,0.002393551,-0.012664023,-0.009768411,-0.043862347,-0.025837826,-0.011187168,-0.041964516,-0.041267447,0.039436467,0.009330833,0.0037426027,-0.03731538,0.006445226,0.020706417,-0.004651441,-0.010126665,0.00781855,0.01164